text.text:
Whether you're killing a couple hours before a gig, meeting up with your homies mid week, or just feeling a touch depleted in the wallet area - there are plenty of times when you want a quick, cheap and tasty feeding. But finding such a thing in the big city can be a bit of a minefield: where can you trust? And more importantly, where can you take your friends without giving everyone a belly ache or, worse, having them judge your taste?

Well don't worry kiddo, we'll show you our favourite Central London cheap eats: wraps, dumplings, noodles, curries and rice bowls - it's all hearty stuff that should go down an absolute treat.

tip.text:
Sometimes, only a good curry will do. Sagar is vegetarian-only, so you can have free rein of the menu and not run into any meaty barriers. There's a pretty huge selection of dishes from all over India (we were impressed with their lentil pizzas called 'uthappams'), and their lassis are great at taking the fire out of anything you may order. Their menu is well marked to help you pick out vegan, nut and gluten-free dishes too, which is always handy.

Sagar’s new Covent Garden outpost is keeping with the no-frills theme, with minimal decor and bland colour schemes. However, with prices that low, they probs don’t have the budget to spruce it up. Don’t miss out on their lunchtime deal of 2 veggie curries, raita, rice, a paratha & a tiny salad for just £3.95 - we dare you to find a better deal in central London.

text.text: Sagar is all veg, so you can have free rein of dishes from all over India. We were impressed with their lentil pizzas called 'uthappams', and their lassis are great at taking the fire out of anything you may have over confidently ordered. Decor is minimal and colour schemes are bland, but their lunchtime deals keep us coming back for more.

tip.text:
This little and lively Lebanese & Middle Eastern is real popular come lunchtime and for good reason. The mixed mezzes, grilled skewers and takeaway wraps are all very tasty, whilst the lunchtime meal deal (£7.50 for a wrap and mezze) is Soho-famous. If you're after a slightly classier lunch than Boots, then this is the place.

It's a cosy wee spot with simple wooden tables, stools and a cute blackboard covered in menu items - we're a sucker for a cute blackboard we are. Pop in for dinner and you'll see slightly less of a rush and slightly more of a chilled cafe vibe - wins.

text.text: This little and lively Lebanese & Middle Eastern can get pretty busy. The mixed mezzes, grilled skewers and takeaway wraps are all very tasty - as are the larger plates like that scrummy lamb shawarma. It's a cosy wee spot with simple wooden tables, stools and a cute blackboard covered in menu items - we're a sucker for a cute blackboard we are.

tip.text: Greasy spoon by day, authentic Thai restaurant by night. Sound familiar? Probably not - because Marie's is truly one-of-a-kind. As soon as 6pm hits, Marie swaps up the fry ups for lemongrass and duck soup - all of which are fragrant and flavourful to the nines. The atmosphere kicks, the dishes are cheap and the joint's a mere hop from Waterloo station. You'd think things couldn't get any better than this, but you'd be wrong. Come nightfall Maria's boasts our favourite kind of policy - that is, BYOB.

tip.text:
The name might sound like some kind of super expensive vegan gluten-free place, but this unglamorous spot actually does a fine line in very cheap, tasty and relatively healthy Korean fast food. Set up similarly to a sandwich bar, plenty of the dishes are around £5 and there's lots to choose from: Korean staples including some really delicious noodle soups, as well as a couple of Japanese highlights (the katsu curry is real popular).

There's always a time and place for a cheap, tasty eat: and plenty of Korean people rate this as a kitchen giving an unusually high level of care and attention to the dishes they serve up.

tip.text:
Do you like frills? If the answer is yes, please move on. But if the answer is 'fuck no I don't like frills at all', let us welcome you into the warming embrace of Paolina's Thai Cafe, where the amiable Paolina serves up homely and satisfying Thai grub within an intimate, authentic-feeling cafe that has all the welcoming vibes you'd like to imagine would greet you were you to stay at someone's house in Thailand.

It's a verified cheap eat with most meals around the £7 mark: our tip would be to come in at lunchtime where you can get into a tasty fragrant green Thai curry for just £6.50. And to top it all off, it's BYOB.

tip.text:
Every so often, we make our way down some grey steps on a non-descript street and get the unmistakable sense we're onto something hot. Roti King really is a king: serving up authentic, tasty and cheap Malaysian food from an open kitchen nook to a tightly packed basement where those in the know squeeze in, wrapping their fingers all over soft flakey rotis dipped in perfectly spiced curries.

When it gets busy - and it does at lunch - a pretty lively hubbub envelops the space, transporting you to a street food canteen someplace exotic where several languages fill the air. The key here is to share a few dishes with a pal or two - and with menu selects coming in at around £7, this is the kind of hidden gem you're going to feel all kinds of smug telling your friends about.

tip.text:
This cute little no frills cafe is a popular Chinatown hangout for the youth (that's us by the way). You can't help but have a soft spot for its pleasing green facade, reasonable prices and generally rough and ready look. And we know those dumplings are made fresh each day 'cause we stood at the window and watched them at it - perhaps for too long.

If you know what's good for you you'll be ordering spicy pork and cabbage pan fried dumplings. Once they've been plonked down in front o' ya (don't expect a smile you old softy) you'll be wanting to dip them in a combination of chilli oil, soy and vinegar. If it's comfort you're after - wontons in broth it is. The chicken broth might be your standard offering but if you're looking for that Chinese childhood nostalgia hit you're onto a winner. There's tea to be had too - classics, greens, floral types (we liked chrysanthemum and honey) and bubble.

text.text: You can't help but have a soft spot for this Chinatown resto's pleasing green facade, reasonable prices and rough-and-ready look. And we know those dumplings are made fresh each day 'cause we stood at the window and watched them at it. Spicy pork and cabbage pan fried dumplings (£5 for 7) are absolute bangers, especially when dipped in chilli oil, soy and vinegar - yum.

tip.text:
They whip up a kati roll so quickly here, you'd think the taste would suffer. No no, me old china, these are spicy wonders. You can get Indian flatbreads or potato rolls filled with chicken tikka, grilled tiger shrimp cooked in coconut milk, and even Indian cheese marinated in a spicy pickle.

Wraps are a dime a dozen in London, but places like the Kati Roll Company keep the whole 'variety is the spice of life' angle nice and, well, spicy.

And you can grab two rolls for under a tenner!

tip.text:
A recent study by the Government found that people who lived in areas with a decent Vietnamese BYOB restaurant were 175% happier. So praise be for King's Cross staple Sen Viet which is exactly as we want it: inexpensive, flavourful and very accommodating to groups who wanna pop a few bottles and get a little loose with their meal.

The decor has that comforting garishness that all reputable Vietnamese places are about: slightly gaudy orange lighting with dark wood and decorative quirks hanging about the place. Food-wise, the extensive menu has all the usual fare ranging from phos to noodles to meat dishes to baguettes. Our tip would be the banh mi heo nuong (chargrilled pork) baguette or the rare beef pho. This is ideal for a group commune and word has spread, so you might need to book.

tip.text:
There might be better places to eat so well for so little £ in these populous ends, but we don’t know many. Al Dente is a pastificio: a takeaway pasta shop where you might grab an indulgent takeaway lunch during the week; buy some tortellini for a slap up meal at home; or come in the evening for a quick, casual feeding. In all cases, you're gonna be extremely satisfied with what your mouth finds.

The pasta, all handmade and served at just the right cottura al dente, is flippin' exquisite, delectable stuff. We sampled some melt-in-the-mouth green tortelli (spinach, mushrooms, ricotta cheese and truffle); and a decadent yet refined carbonara. Yes this is pure, authentic Italian cooking and, with dishes around the £6.50-7 mark, it's an excellent cheap eat. Get in, grab a plate of pasta and a glass of wine, chomp it, sip it, feel good, reflect on your standing in the world, then move slowly onwards.

Walk-ins only.

tip.text:
This late-night Chinese noodle bar is cheap, fast, and entirely frill-less. But we’ll take thrills over frills any day - in this case, the thrill of watching your noodles hand-pulled before your very eyes.

They come in two variants: dao xiao mian (fat, flat strips); and la-mian (your classic spaghetti-looking number). Take your pick and watch as the chef pulls, flips, chops and flicks your noodles into shape before serving them fried, dry or in a soup. Our humble tip would be to take a mate and get one portion fried with succulent, rich roast duck, and one portion of the dan-dan soup. Maybe best to take a mate you don’t mind getting a bit messy with, however.

Speaking of messy, they’re open till the early hours (2am weekdays, 5am weekends), ideal for a late-night slurp sesh. Just be sure to stick to the noodles and avoid the luminous orange dishes in the window.

tip.text:
This is one of those rare finds that is so low-key, authentic and weird that you can't help but feel smug having 'discovered' it/read about it on your favourite lifestyle app. The canteen to the drab, brutalist Indian YMCA in Fitzrovia, it immediately reminds us of being in school - had we gone to school in Delhi and if the curries had been 300 times better (A for effort though, Jamie).

Anyone who has been to Indiyar will recognise the gargantuan portions of rice that serve as the base for your meal; from there just pick a couple of curries, a daal, some eye-wateringly salty lime pickle, a paratha, and maybe a mango lassi, and you'll still be under a tenner. At dinner and weekend lunch they have a set menu for £9 that will leave the hungriest of you satisfied.

tip.text:
This friendly no-frills spot may not be a looker but by George does it feed you up. The laid-back feel, simple decor and hearty dishes make it perfect for a casual weekday dinner or a late night catch up with pals. What says friendship better than a menu of homely Malaysian and Singaporean dishes from laksa to workaday Hainanese chicken with a Tsing Tao beer?

Tuck into noodle soups, fried veggie rice, grilled meat skewers and all sorts of seafood. Coconut lovers would do well with a beef rendang, while simple sods like you and we might enjoy the comforting flavours of a char kway teow (smokey stir-fried flat noodles with pork and prawns) - not too shabby for eight bob. Feel free to order glutinous desserts - at your own risk - but we'd go for a trip through the enlightening drinks list: where hot tea, iced tea and bubble tea sit beside chocolatey malt drinks (milo dinosaur) and Malaysian coffee with condensed milk (kopi). Yep it's a wild old ride.

tip.text:
Xi'an Impression has quietly been pumping out regional, authentic street food from north-western China to happy Highbury punters for years now. But not content to stay as a pokey hidden gem, they've made a leap for the big leagues with a comparatively vast canteen space on Commercial Street.

Despite feeling a little jaded that the suits and boots of Aldgate are now in on our secret, we're happy to report that the food is just as excellent, exciting and occasionally weird as it's always been. As with the original, the menu has a distinctly bitter and savoury theme, with oddities like black fungus and domes of boneless chicken that come swimming in rich, nutty sauces and oils, with hints of the Silk Road's Middle Eastern influences shining through. Our favourite new addition is the hand-pulled biangbiang noodles with cumin and lamb - the noodles thick and chewy and the lamb tender and richly seasoned in flavours that contrast beautifully with the East Asian textures.

tip.text:
We've long seen the queues outside OnTheBab, on Old Street, and wondered just what's going on inside. Well, it's food. South Korean comfort food to be a little more precise. A quick and casual place for dinner, come here to treat yourself and indulge. The spicy pork bun and the fried chicken with fried peanut were the dishes that really got us going. Let that rich sauce and flavour bring you happiness. That happiness won't last forever, but nothing really does.

Top Tip: keep an eye on the small window where you can either see the hands of a chef preparing the food or an actor pretending to be a chef preparing the food.
